# Directed Graph

A **Directed Graph (Digraph)** is a graph in which each edge has a specific direction. An edge from one vertex to another does not imply
a connection in the opposite direction.

### Example

```text
A → B
↓
C
```

### Characteristics

* Edges have direction.
* Relationships are one-way.
* Traversal follows edge directions.

### Advantages

* Represents directional relationships.
* Useful for dependency modeling.
* Suitable for process flows.

### Disadvantages

* More complex than undirected graphs.
* Traversal requires careful handling of directions.

### Applications

* Website linking.
* Task scheduling.
* Airline route systems.
* Dependency management.

---

# Undirected Graph

An **Undirected Graph** is a graph in which edges do not have directions. If a connection exists between two vertices, movement is 
possible in both directions.

### Example

```text
A ----- B
|
|
C
```

### Characteristics

* No edge direction.
* Two-way relationships.
* Simpler structure.

### Advantages

* Easy implementation.
* Simple traversal.
* Suitable for mutual relationships.

### Disadvantages

* Cannot represent one-way relationships.
* Less suitable for dependency-based problems.

### Applications

* Friendship networks.
* Road maps.
* Communication networks.
* Utility networks.

---

# Difference Between Directed and Undirected Graph

| Feature        | Directed Graph  | Undirected Graph |
| -------------- | --------------- | ---------------- |
| Edge Direction | Present         | Absent           |
| Relationship   | One-way         | Two-way          |
| Complexity     | Higher          | Lower            |
| Traversal      | Direction Based | Bidirectional    |
| Example        | Twitter Follow  | Facebook Friend  |

---

# Difference Between Adjacency Matrix and Adjacency List

| Feature             | Adjacency Matrix | Adjacency List |
| ------------------- | ---------------- | -------------- |
| Storage Requirement | O(V²)            | O(V+E)         |
| Memory Usage        | High             | Low            |
| Edge Search         | Fast             | Slow           |
| Best For            | Dense Graphs     | Sparse Graphs  |
| Implementation      | Simple           | Moderate       |

